tion","Draws water into the intestinal lumen via osmotic gradient","Increases chloride secretion into the intestinal lumen","Softens stool by acting as a surfactant","Stimulates release of intestinal prostaglandins"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOsmotic laxatives work by \u003Cstrong\u003Edrawing water into the intestinal lumen via osmotic gradient\u003C/strong\u003E. These agents are poorly absorbed and create an osmotic gradient that pulls water into the bowel, softening stool and promoting bowel movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating release of intestinal prostaglandins\u003C/strong\u003E is not the primary mechanism of osmotic laxatives, though some laxatives may have effects on prostaglandin pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly stimulating intestinal smooth muscle contraction\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of stimulant laxatives such as bisacodyl.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESoftening stool by acting as a surfactant\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of stool softeners such as docusate sodium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing chloride secretion into the intestinal lumen\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of secretagogue laxatives such as lubiprostone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon examples of osmotic laxatives include polyethylene glycol, lactulose, and magnesium salts. These medications are effective for treating constipation but may take 24-48 hours to work.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osmotic laxatives work by drawing water into the intestinal lumen through osmotic forces.","Polyethylene glycol is a non-absorbable osmotic laxative that does not cause 